  <!-- MODULE 1: YOUR GAP REPORT -->
  <div id="apn-nutr-m1" class="apn-nutr-section" style="background:#FFFFFF;">
    <div class="apn-nutr-inner">
      <span class="apn-nutr-label">Your Current State</span>
      <h2 class="apn-nutr-h2">What Your Score Actually Means</h2>
      <div class="apn-nutr-divider"></div>

      <p class="apn-nutr-body">
        Your Nutrition score of <strong id="apn-nutr-m1-score"></strong>/100 is not a grade. It is a measurement of how well your current eating structure supports the physiological demands of consistent training. Here is what that number means in real terms.
      </p>

      <div id="apn-nutr-score-context" style="margin:28px 0;"></div>

      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:12px;">What a 90+ Score Looks Like</h3>
      <p class="apn-nutr-body">
        An athlete scoring 90 or above on nutrition is hitting 0.9 to 1.0 grams of protein per pound of bodyweight daily, distributed across 4 to 5 meals. Each meal clears the 2.5g leucine threshold needed to trigger the mTOR pathway and maximize muscle protein synthesis (MPS). They eat more carbohydrates on training days (3 to 5g per pound) and fewer on rest days (1.5 to 2g per pound). Their Vitamin D, Magnesium, and Zinc levels are within optimal ranges. Meals are consistent, not reactive. Hunger is rare because meal structure prevents it.
      </p>

      <div style="background:#0D0D0D;color:#F8FAFB;padding:24px 28px;margin:32px 0;border-radius:4px;">
        <p style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:32px;font-weight:bold;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Up to 25%</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:14px;color:#9CA3AF;margin:0;">Estimated reduction in muscle protein synthesis when protein is consumed in 1 to 2 large meals vs. 4 to 5 distributed meals with equivalent total intake. Source: Journal of Nutrition, leucine distribution studies.</p>
      </div>

      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:32px;">The Performance Tax You Are Paying Right Now</h3>
      <p class="apn-nutr-body">
        Nutrition gaps do not announce themselves. They show up as flat training sessions, slower recovery, afternoon energy crashes, and strength gains that stall for no clear reason. If you are under-eating protein relative to your training demand, your body is breaking down muscle tissue to meet amino acid needs between meals. If your carbohydrate timing is off, your glycogen stores are chronically low during sessions, and your output is capped 15 to 20% below what your fitness level should produce. This is not a motivation problem. It is a fueling problem.
      </p>

      <!-- TIER CONDITIONAL FRAMING -->
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="rookie" style="border-left:4px solid #22C55E;background:#F0FDF4;padding:20px 24px;margin:28px 0;border-radius:0 4px 4px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#22C55E;margin:0 0 8px;">Rookie Tier</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Nutrition is the most important single change you will make this month. Your training creates the demand. What you eat determines whether your body can meet it. Everything else, sleep, recovery, supplementation, amplifies what you build here. Lock this in first.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="competitor" style="border-left:4px solid #F59E0B;background:#FFFBEB;padding:20px 24px;margin:28px 0;border-radius:0 4px 4px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#F59E0B;margin:0 0 8px;">Competitor Tier</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">One gap is holding back all your other training adaptation. This is it. Your basics are in place. Your nutrition structure is inconsistent enough that it is negating some of what your training builds. Close this gap first. Everything else is secondary.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="athlete" style="border-left:4px solid #06A5C5;background:#F0FBFD;padding:20px 24px;margin:28px 0;border-radius:0 4px 4px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Athlete Tier</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">You are in the optimization zone. Your foundation is solid. The gap between where you are and your performance ceiling is now a precision problem. Protein distribution, carb timing, and micronutrient coverage are where the remaining gains live.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="elite" style="border-left:4px solid #8B5CF6;background:#F5F3FF;padding:20px 24px;margin:28px 0;border-radius:0 4px 4px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#8B5CF6;margin:0 0 8px;">Elite Tier</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">At your level, nutrition is a precision variable. The margin between good and great lives in the details: exact leucine counts per meal, carb periodization by training block, and micronutrient status confirmed by bloodwork. The gap is narrow. The impact is not.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="champion" style="border-left:4px solid #EF4444;background:#FEF2F2;padding:20px 24px;margin:28px 0;border-radius:0 4px 4px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#EF4444;margin:0 0 8px;">Champion Tier</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Protect this. A nutrition system that works at your level took months to build. If it degrades, the cascade hits every other pillar within 2 to 3 weeks. Do not assume consistency. Verify it.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- QUICK WIN -->
      <div style="border-top:3px solid #06A5C5;background:#F4F4F2;padding:24px 28px;margin:32px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:4px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 10px;">Your Quick Win Today</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">At your next meal, add a protein source that brings the total protein content to at least 30 grams. Chicken breast (3.5oz = 30g), Greek yogurt (1 cup = 17g, pair with 2 eggs = 12g), or a whey shake (25 to 30g). The reason: this single meal must clear the 2.5g leucine threshold to activate mTOR and trigger muscle protein synthesis. Below that threshold, you get suboptimal MPS regardless of your total daily protein intake. One meal. Right now. Done.</p>
      </div>
