      <h2 class="apn-nutr-h2">The Mechanism Behind Your Nutrition Gap</h2>
      <div class="apn-nutr-divider"></div>

      <p class="apn-nutr-body">
        The central issue is not total calories. It is not even total protein. It is the biological machinery that determines whether the protein you eat gets used to build muscle or simply gets oxidized for energy. That machinery has a specific trigger: the leucine threshold.
      </p>

      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:12px;">The Leucine Threshold and mTOR Activation</h3>
      <p class="apn-nutr-body">
        Leucine is the amino acid that directly activates mTOR (mechanistic target of rapamycin), the primary signaling pathway for muscle protein synthesis. The threshold is 2.5 to 3 grams of leucine per meal. Below that level, the mTOR signal is insufficient and MPS is not maximally stimulated, regardless of how much total protein is consumed that day. A 30g dose of whey protein contains approximately 2.7g of leucine and clears the threshold. A 30g dose of most plant proteins does not, because the leucine fraction is lower and digestibility is reduced.
      </p>
      <p class="apn-nutr-body">
        The practical implication: eating 120g of protein across two 60g meals is significantly less effective for MPS than eating 120g across four 30g meals. The mTOR signal saturates at around 30 to 40g per meal and the excess is oxidized. You need 4 to 5 leucine threshold triggers per day, not just one or two large ones.
      </p>

      <div style="background:#0D0D0D;color:#F8FAFB;padding:24px 28px;margin:32px 0;border-radius:4px;">
        <p style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:32px;font-weight:bold;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">4x vs. 2x</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:14px;color:#9CA3AF;margin:0;">Four leucine-threshold meals per day triggers mTOR signaling 4 separate times, compared to 2 activations from two large meals with identical total protein. Each activation window is 2 to 3 hours. Missing activations equals missed adaptation.</p>
      </div>

      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:32px;">Carbohydrate Periodization and Glycogen</h3>
      <p class="apn-nutr-body">
        Muscle glycogen is the primary fuel for high-intensity training. Glycogen is synthesized from dietary carbohydrate. If carbohydrate intake does not match training demand, glycogen stores deplete across training days and performance drops measurably. On training days with 60 to 90 minutes of high-intensity work, carbohydrate needs run 3 to 5g per pound of bodyweight. On rest days, 1.5 to 2g per pound is appropriate. Eating the same amount of carbohydrates every day means you are under-fueling training days and over-fueling rest days simultaneously.
      </p>

      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:32px;">Micronutrient Deficits and the Silent Performance Tax</h3>
      <p class="apn-nutr-body">
        Three micronutrients are deficient in the majority of serious training athletes, and all three directly impair physical performance when low.
      </p>
      <ul style="list-style:none;margin:16px 0 24px;">
        <li style="padding:12px 0 12px 24px;border-bottom:1px solid #E2E8F0;position:relative;font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;"><span style="position:absolute;left:0;top:16px;width:8px;height:8px;border-radius:50%;background:#06A5C5;display:block;"></span><strong>Vitamin D:</strong> Deficiency is linked to reduced muscle strength, impaired neuromuscular function, and shorter slow-wave sleep cycles (which reduces overnight GH release). Optimal range for athletes: 50 to 70 ng/mL. Most untested athletes sit at 20 to 35 ng/mL.</li>
        <li style="padding:12px 0 12px 24px;border-bottom:1px solid #E2E8F0;position:relative;font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;"><span style="position:absolute;left:0;top:16px;width:8px;height:8px;border-radius:50%;background:#06A5C5;display:block;"></span><strong>Magnesium:</strong> Required cofactor for over 300 enzymatic reactions including ATP synthesis, protein synthesis, and muscle contraction. Athletes lose magnesium through sweat. Deficiency increases HPA axis reactivity and elevates baseline cortisol, which is directly catabolic to muscle.</li>
        <li style="padding:12px 0 12px 24px;position:relative;font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;"><span style="position:absolute;left:0;top:16px;width:8px;height:8px;border-radius:50%;background:#06A5C5;display:block;"></span><strong>Zinc:</strong> Required for testosterone synthesis and is a cofactor for IGF-1 signaling. Clinically significant zinc deficiency in athletes is associated with 20 to 25% lower testosterone levels and impaired satellite cell activation post-training.</li>
      </ul>

      <!-- COMPOUNDING EFFECT -->
      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:32px;">How This Gap Degrades Your Other Pillars</h3>
      <p class="apn-nutr-body">
        Nutrition does not exist in isolation. An inconsistent protein distribution directly limits recovery: even with optimal sleep, you cannot rebuild muscle tissue you are not providing adequate amino acids for. Chronic under-fueling on training days elevates cortisol (the body's response to perceived energy scarcity), which degrades sleep quality and blunts anabolic hormone output. Magnesium deficiency impairs sleep onset and sleep quality simultaneously. A nutrition gap ripples across recovery, sleep, and hormonal health within days of consistent under-eating.
      </p>

      <!-- COMMON MISTAKE -->
      <div style="border-left:4px solid #F59E0B;background:#FFFBEB;padding:16px 20px;margin:24px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#F59E0B;margin:0 0 8px;">Common Mistake</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Eating a very large protein meal at dinner and assuming it compensates for low protein earlier in the day. It does not. The mTOR pathway saturates at approximately 30 to 40g and the remaining amino acids are oxidized for energy. Your 80g dinner has the same MPS yield as a 35g dinner. The protein distribution window cannot be retrieved retroactively.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- TIER CONDITIONAL COST BLOCKS -->
      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:16px;margin-top:32px;">What This Gap Costs at Your Level</h3>

      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="rookie">
        <p class="apn-nutr-body">At the Rookie level, a nutrition gap is costing you the majority of your potential training adaptation. Your body is going through the motions of training without the raw materials to build anything. Every session you complete without adequate protein distribution is a session that produced approximately 30 to 50% of the muscle protein synthesis it could have. You are building a foundation with gaps in it.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="competitor">
        <p class="apn-nutr-body">At the Competitor level, this gap is a ceiling. Your training quality is good enough that your body is generating a strong MPS signal, but inconsistent nutrition means that signal is only being met half the time. Your recovery is slower than it should be, your strength gains are stalling earlier than they should, and your energy during the last 20 minutes of sessions is lower than your fitness level warrants.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="athlete">
        <p class="apn-nutr-body">At the Athlete level, the cost is precision. You are likely hitting total protein targets on average but not meal-by-meal. The 1 to 2 MPS triggers you are missing per day add up to 30 to 60 missed triggers per month. That compounds. You are also likely leaving carbohydrate periodization gains on the table: an estimated 10 to 15% more training output is available on your high-intensity days if glycogen is fully topped off beforehand.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="elite">
        <p class="apn-nutr-body">At the Elite level, this gap shows up in bloodwork and recovery metrics before it shows up in performance. Sub-optimal Vitamin D and zinc levels are the most common finding at this tier. The cost is not dramatic performance loss. It is a 3 to 5% suppression across strength, testosterone, and sleep quality simultaneously. Small numbers. Large impact compounded over a competitive season.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="champion">
        <p class="apn-nutr-body">At the Champion level, any nutrition regression triggers a measurable cascade within 2 weeks. HRV drops. Sleep quality degrades. Strength metrics soften. The cost is not the gap itself. It is the recovery time required to rebuild what the gap eroded. Protect the structure you have built. It is harder to rebuild than to maintain.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- MODULE 3: THE DIAGNOSIS -->
  <div id="apn-nutr-m3" class="apn-nutr-section" style="background:#FFFFFF;">
    <div class="apn-nutr-inner">
      <span class="apn-nutr-label">Self-Assessment</span>
      <h2 class="apn-nutr-h2">Identify Your Specific Nutrition Problem</h2>
      <div class="apn-nutr-divider"></div>

      <p class="apn-nutr-body">Your quiz score gives us the what. This assessment identifies the why. Check every symptom that applies to your current nutrition reality. Be honest. The protocol you build in Module 4 is only as targeted as this diagnosis.</p>
      <p class="apn-nutr-body">Your current Nutrition score: <strong id="apn-nutr-m3-score" style="color:#06A5C5;font-size:18px;"></strong>/100.</p>

      <div id="apn-nutr-checkboxes" style="margin:28px 0;">
        <label class="apn-nutr-checkbox-item">
          <input type="checkbox" class="apn-nutr-symptom" onchange="apnNutrUpdateSeverity()">
          <label>I struggle to consistently hit 0.8 to 1 gram of protein per pound of bodyweight on most days.</label>
        </label>
        <label class="apn-nutr-checkbox-item">
          <input type="checkbox" class="apn-nutr-symptom" onchange="apnNutrUpdateSeverity()">
          <label>I feel flat or noticeably weaker during training sessions that should feel productive.</label>
        </label>
        <label class="apn-nutr-checkbox-item">
          <input type="checkbox" class="apn-nutr-symptom" onchange="apnNutrUpdateSeverity()">
          <label>I skip meals regularly or eat the same 3 to 4 foods without a real structure to it.</label>
        </label>
        <label class="apn-nutr-checkbox-item">
          <input type="checkbox" class="apn-nutr-symptom" onchange="apnNutrUpdateSeverity()">
          <label>I get hungry 2 to 3 hours after eating, which tells me my meals are not protein and fat sufficient.</label>
        </label>
        <label class="apn-nutr-checkbox-item">
          <input type="checkbox" class="apn-nutr-symptom" onchange="apnNutrUpdateSeverity()">
          <label>My energy crashes mid-afternoon and I reach for caffeine or snacks to get through it.</label>
        </label>
        <label class="apn-nutr-checkbox-item">
          <input type="checkbox" class="apn-nutr-symptom" onchange="apnNutrUpdateSeverity()">
          <label>I eat the majority of my protein in one or two large meals rather than across 4 to 5 meals.</label>
        </label>
        <label class="apn-nutr-checkbox-item">
          <input type="checkbox" class="apn-nutr-symptom" onchange="apnNutrUpdateSeverity()">
          <label>I do not track my macros and have no reliable sense of what my average intake actually looks like.</label>
        </label>
      </div>

      <div id="apn-nutr-severity"></div>

      <!-- SUB-GAP IDENTIFICATION -->
      <div style="margin-top:40px;">
        <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:22px;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:12px;">Your Three Most Likely Root Causes</h3>
        <p class="apn-nutr-body">Based on your quiz score and tier, your nutrition gap most likely traces to one of these three sub-gaps. Select the one that resonates most. Your Module 4 protocol will be anchored to it.</p>

        <button class="apn-nutr-subgap-btn" onclick="apnNutrSelectSubgap(this, 'Protein Under-Eating')">
          <span>Sub-Gap 1: Protein Under-Eating</span><br>
          <span style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:13px;color:#6B7280;font-weight:400;">You are not hitting your daily protein target consistently, and when you do, it is concentrated in too few meals to trigger enough MPS activation cycles.</span>
        </button>
        <button class="apn-nutr-subgap-btn" onclick="apnNutrSelectSubgap(this, 'Poor Carb Timing')">
          <span>Sub-Gap 2: Poor Carb Timing</span><br>
          <span style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:13px;color:#6B7280;font-weight:400;">Your total carbohydrate intake may be adequate but it is not matched to training days. Glycogen stores are low when you need them most and your training output is capped as a result.</span>
        </button>
        <button class="apn-nutr-subgap-btn" onclick="apnNutrSelectSubgap(this, 'Micronutrient Gaps')">
          <span>Sub-Gap 3: Micronutrient Gaps</span><br>
          <span style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:13px;color:#6B7280;font-weight:400;">Your macronutrient structure is reasonable but Vitamin D, Magnesium, or Zinc deficiencies are silently reducing muscle function, testosterone output, and sleep quality.</span>
        </button>

        <div id="apn-nutr-primary-target">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin-bottom:8px;">Your Primary Target</p>
          <p id="apn-nutr-target-text" style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:16px;font-weight:700;color:#0D0D0D;margin:0;"></p>
        </div>
