  <!-- MODULE 4: THE PROTOCOL -->
  <div id="apn-nutr-m4" class="apn-nutr-section" style="background:#F4F4F2;">
    <div class="apn-nutr-inner">
      <span class="apn-nutr-label">The Protocol</span>
      <h2 class="apn-nutr-h2">Your 30-Day Nutrition Closure Plan</h2>
      <div class="apn-nutr-divider"></div>

      <p class="apn-nutr-body">Four weeks. One gap. Here is exactly what to do. Every action has a what, a dose or amount, a timing, and a mechanism. Nothing vague. Execute this in sequence and measure the result at Day 30.</p>

      <!-- WEEK 1 -->
      <div class="apn-nutr-week">
        <p class="apn-nutr-week-header">Week 1</p>
        <h3 class="apn-nutr-week-title">Calculate and Track Your Protein Target</h3>
        <p class="apn-nutr-body">This week is entirely about establishing your baseline. You cannot close a gap you have not measured. No changes yet beyond tracking.</p>

        <ul class="apn-nutr-action-list">
          <li><strong>Calculate your protein target:</strong> Multiply your bodyweight in pounds by 0.9. That is your daily minimum in grams. A 185-pound athlete targets 167g minimum daily. Use 1.0g/lb if you are in a muscle-building phase.</li>
          <li><strong>Download MyFitnessPal or Cronometer:</strong> Log every meal for 7 days. You are not optimizing yet. You are collecting honest data. Most athletes discover they are hitting 50 to 70% of their protein target, not 80 to 90% as they assumed.</li>
          <li><strong>Note meal timing:</strong> Record what time each meal happens and the protein content of each. Look for the pattern: most athletes find 70% of their protein in the last 2 meals of the day.</li>
          <li><strong>Identify your protein sources:</strong> List which foods are reliably getting you to 25 to 30g per meal. These become your non-negotiables in Week 2.</li>
        </ul>

        <!-- TIER CONDITIONAL WEEK 1 -->
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="rookie" style="background:#F0FDF4;border:1px solid #22C55E;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#22C55E;margin-bottom:8px;">Rookie: One Thing This Week</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Track protein only. Not calories. Not carbs. Not fat. Protein grams per day for 7 days. Write it in your phone notes if you do not want an app. One metric. That is your entire job this week.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="competitor" style="background:#FFFBEB;border:1px solid #F59E0B;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#F59E0B;margin-bottom:8px;">Competitor: Track Protein Timing</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Track total daily protein AND the time of each meal. You need to see the distribution pattern. Is your protein front-loaded or back-loaded? The answer changes your Week 2 strategy.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="athlete" style="background:#F0FBFD;border:1px solid #06A5C5;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#06A5C5;margin-bottom:8px;">Athlete: Full Macro Tracking</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Track protein, carbs, and meal timing. Calculate carbohydrate intake on training days vs. rest days and compare them. You are looking for whether your carb intake is periodized or flat across the week.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="elite" style="background:#F5F3FF;border:1px solid #8B5CF6;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#8B5CF6;margin-bottom:8px;">Elite: Baseline and Bloodwork</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Full macro tracking plus schedule a Vitamin D, Magnesium RBC, and Zinc panel if not done in the last 6 months. You cannot optimize micronutrient status without a baseline number. Order through your primary care physician or a lab like LabCorp.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="champion" style="background:#FEF2F2;border:1px solid #EF4444;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#EF4444;margin-bottom:8px;">Champion: Verify Your System</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Use Week 1 to audit your current structure against the leucine threshold standard. Is every meal clearing 2.5g leucine? Run the numbers. Identify any meal that is not, and flag it for Week 2 correction.</p>
        </div>

        <div style="border-top:3px solid #06A5C5;background:#fff;padding:24px 28px;margin:24px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:4px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 10px;">Week 1 Assignment</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Track your protein intake every day this week. At the end of Day 7, calculate your average daily intake and compare it to your target (bodyweight x 0.9). Write down your biggest protein distribution gap: which meal consistently falls below 25g? That is your Week 2 target.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- WEEK 2 -->
      <div class="apn-nutr-week">
        <p class="apn-nutr-week-header">Week 2</p>
        <h3 class="apn-nutr-week-title">Fix Protein Distribution Across 4 Meals</h3>
        <p class="apn-nutr-body">You have your data. Now you fix the structure. Every meal this week must hit 25 to 30g of protein. Four meals minimum. This triggers the mTOR pathway 4 separate times per day.</p>

        <ul class="apn-nutr-action-list">
          <li><strong>Meal 1 (within 90 min of waking):</strong> 3 whole eggs + 1 cup Greek yogurt = approximately 29g protein, 2.6g leucine. This clears the threshold. Add 1 cup oats if training later that morning.</li>
          <li><strong>Meal 2 (midday):</strong> 5oz chicken breast or 6oz ground beef = 30 to 35g protein. Pair with 1 cup rice (training day) or 1 cup mixed vegetables (rest day). The protein count is the fixed variable. The carbohydrate is the flexible one.</li>
          <li><strong>Meal 3 (pre or post training window):</strong> If training within 2 hours, prioritize carbohydrates (50 to 75g) plus 25g protein. If post-training, consume 25 to 30g protein within 45 minutes. The acute MPS window is highest in the 0 to 2 hours post-training.</li>
          <li><strong>Meal 4 (evening, 2 to 3 hrs before bed):</strong> 6oz salmon or 6oz beef = 30 to 35g protein. Casein protein (cottage cheese, 1 cup = 25g) is optimal here due to slow-release amino acid delivery overnight. This sustains MPS during the 7 to 8 hour overnight fast.</li>
        </ul>

        <!-- TIER CONDITIONAL WEEK 2 -->
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="rookie" style="background:#F0FDF4;border:1px solid #22C55E;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#22C55E;margin-bottom:8px;">Rookie: Master Two Meals First</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Do not try to fix all four meals at once. Pick the two meals you eat most consistently and lock in 25 to 30g protein at each. Add meals 3 and 4 in Week 3. Consistency beats completeness at this stage.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="competitor" style="background:#FFFBEB;border:1px solid #F59E0B;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#F59E0B;margin-bottom:8px;">Competitor: Four Meals, Fixed Protein</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Four meals. Every day. Each one at 25g minimum. This is the primary change this week. Do not complicate it. Prep 2 to 3 days of meals in advance so the decision is already made when the day gets busy.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="athlete" style="background:#F0FBFD;border:1px solid #06A5C5;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#06A5C5;margin-bottom:8px;">Athlete: Add Intra-Workout Protein Timing</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Lock four leucine-threshold meals, then optimize your training window. For sessions over 75 minutes, consider 10 to 15g of fast-absorbing protein (EAAs or whey) intra-workout to sustain MPS signaling during the session itself.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="elite" style="background:#F5F3FF;border:1px solid #8B5CF6;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#8B5CF6;margin-bottom:8px;">Elite: Leucine Counts Per Meal</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Calculate actual leucine content per meal, not just protein grams. Animal proteins average 8 to 9% leucine by weight. Plant proteins average 6 to 7%. If you use any plant-based sources, you need 35 to 40g total protein to clear the same leucine threshold as 30g of whey.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="champion" style="background:#FEF2F2;border:1px solid #EF4444;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#EF4444;margin-bottom:8px;">Champion: Protect the System</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Verify that your current meal structure is delivering leucine threshold clears at every eating occasion. If travel, competition, or schedule disruption is a recurring factor, build a backup protocol: two or three portable meals that hit the threshold regardless of environment.</p>
        </div>

        <div style="border-top:3px solid #06A5C5;background:#fff;padding:24px 28px;margin:24px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:4px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 10px;">Week 2 Assignment</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Hit 4 meals at 25g protein minimum for 5 out of 7 days. On Day 14, check: are you hungry between meals less often than Week 1? Is your mid-afternoon energy more consistent? These are the first measurable signals that protein distribution is improving.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SCRIPTURE BLOCK - placed naturally mid-protocol -->
      <div style="text-align:center;padding:40px 24px;margin:48px 0;background:#fff;">
        <p style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-style:italic;font-size:17px;color:#0D0D0D;max-width:520px;margin:0 auto;line-height:1.65;">"Do you not know that your bodies are temples of the Holy Spirit, who is in you, whom you have received from God? You are not your own; you were bought at a price. Therefore honor God with your bodies."</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:4px;color:#06A5C5;margin-top:16px;">1 Corinthians 6:19-20</p>
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:14px;color:#6B7280;margin-top:12px;max-width:480px;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;line-height:1.6;">Stewardship is not a spiritual concept disconnected from nutrition. Feeding your body with precision and intentionality is an act of honoring what you have been given. The discipline it takes to eat well is the same discipline that builds character in every other area of life.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- WEEK 3 -->
      <div class="apn-nutr-week">
        <p class="apn-nutr-week-header">Week 3</p>
        <h3 class="apn-nutr-week-title">Introduce Carbohydrate Periodization</h3>
        <p class="apn-nutr-body">Protein distribution is now your habit. Week 3 adds a second variable: matching carbohydrate intake to training demand. Your protein stays fixed. Your carbohydrates flex based on the day's energy requirement.</p>

        <ul class="apn-nutr-action-list">
          <li><strong>Training day carbohydrate target:</strong> 3 to 4g per pound of bodyweight for moderate training. 4 to 5g per pound for high-intensity sessions (hard sparring, max effort lifting, long conditioning). A 185-pound athlete needs 555 to 740g carbohydrates on a hard training day. This is not optional. It is what keeps glycogen topped off for session quality.</li>
          <li><strong>Rest day carbohydrate target:</strong> 1.5 to 2g per pound of bodyweight. Same athlete: 277 to 370g on rest days. The reduction is approximately 40 to 50% of training day intake. Protein stays the same. Total calories drop moderately.</li>
          <li><strong>Carb timing on training days:</strong> Load the majority pre-training. 75 to 100g of carbohydrate in the meal 2 to 3 hours before training. 50g in the hour before if a full meal is not possible. Post-training: 50 to 75g carbohydrates with 25 to 30g protein within 45 minutes. This is when glycogen resynthesis is fastest.</li>
          <li><strong>Carb sources that matter:</strong> White rice, oats, sweet potato, banana, and fruit are optimal before training. Whole grain, high-fiber sources (broccoli, legumes) belong on rest days or away from training windows because fiber slows digestion and blunts glucose delivery timing.</li>
        </ul>

        <!-- TIER CONDITIONAL WEEK 3 -->
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="rookie" style="background:#F0FDF4;border:1px solid #22C55E;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#22C55E;margin-bottom:8px;">Rookie: Two Categories Only</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Do not calculate exact gram targets yet. Just divide your week into training days and rest days. On training days, eat more carbohydrates. On rest days, eat fewer. That single structural change will improve training energy noticeably.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="competitor" style="background:#FFFBEB;border:1px solid #F59E0B;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#F59E0B;margin-bottom:8px;">Competitor: Hit the Pre-Training Window</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Focus your carbohydrate periodization on the 2-hour pre-training meal. Get 75g of easily digested carbohydrates in that window on every training day. This is where most Competitors lose training performance: they go into hard sessions under-fueled.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="athlete" style="background:#F0FBFD;border:1px solid #06A5C5;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#06A5C5;margin-bottom:8px;">Athlete: Track Training-Day vs. Rest-Day Intake</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Run the numbers. Calculate your average carbohydrate intake on training days and compare it to rest days. The gap should be 40 to 50%. If the gap is less than 20%, your periodization is effectively flat. Adjust intentionally.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="elite" style="background:#F5F3FF;border:1px solid #8B5CF6;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#8B5CF6;margin-bottom:8px;">Elite: Block Periodization by Training Phase</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Align carbohydrate intake to your training block structure, not just daily training status. High-volume training phases warrant a 15 to 20% higher weekly carbohydrate average. Deload weeks warrant a 20% reduction. Flat carbohydrate intake across varied training phases is leaving adaptation on the table.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="champion" style="background:#FEF2F2;border:1px solid #EF4444;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#EF4444;margin-bottom:8px;">Champion: Competition Calendar Periodization</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Your carbohydrate periodization should extend to the competition calendar. Peak carbohydrate loading (6 to 8g/lb) in the 48 hours before a competition or event. Taper carbohydrates 7 to 10 days out to reduce body water if weight class matters, then reload aggressively in the final 48 hours.</p>
        </div>

        <div style="border-top:3px solid #06A5C5;background:#fff;padding:24px 28px;margin:24px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:4px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 10px;">Week 3 Assignment</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">On your next 3 training days, add 50 to 75g of carbohydrate to your pre-training meal (2 to 3 hours before training). Note how your energy feels in the first 30 minutes of the session compared to sessions where you were under-fueled. The difference is often dramatic within one week.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- WEEK 4 -->
      <div class="apn-nutr-week">
        <p class="apn-nutr-week-header">Week 4</p>
        <h3 class="apn-nutr-week-title">Add the Micronutrient Stack and Review Energy Consistency</h3>
        <p class="apn-nutr-body">Weeks 1 through 3 fixed your macronutrient architecture. Week 4 completes the foundation by addressing the micronutrient gaps that silently undermine everything you have built.</p>

        <ul class="apn-nutr-action-list">
          <li><strong>Vitamin D3: 2,000 to 5,000 IU daily</strong> with a fat-containing meal. If you have bloodwork, target serum 25(OH)D between 50 and 70 ng/mL. Without bloodwork, 3,000 IU daily with lunch is a safe and effective starting point for most athletes. Mechanism: restores neuromuscular signaling efficiency and supports slow-wave sleep quality for overnight GH release.</li>
          <li><strong>Magnesium Glycinate: 400mg at night</strong>, 60 minutes before bed. Glycinate form is preferred over oxide because it is better absorbed and does not cause GI distress. Mechanism: cofactor for ATP synthesis and muscle contraction. Also modulates GABA, which reduces sleep onset latency and improves deep sleep architecture.</li>
          <li><strong>Zinc: 25 to 30mg daily</strong> with food. Do not exceed 40mg without medical supervision. Zinc competes with copper for absorption at high doses. Mechanism: cofactor for testosterone synthesis via the hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal axis. Also required for IGF-1 signaling and satellite cell activation post-training.</li>
          <li><strong>Greens supplement:</strong> 1 serving daily in water or a smoothie, taken in the morning. This covers the micronutrient gaps between whole food intake and what performance demands. Look for Vitamin K2, B-vitamins, and adaptogenic botanicals in the formulation.</li>
        </ul>

        <!-- TIER CONDITIONAL WEEK 4 -->
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="rookie" style="background:#F0FDF4;border:1px solid #22C55E;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#22C55E;margin-bottom:8px;">Rookie: Start with Greens and Vitamin D</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Two additions this week: a greens supplement in the morning and Vitamin D3 at lunch. Do not try to add all three micronutrients at once. Lock these two before adding Magnesium and Zinc. Your energy consistency should be measurably better by Day 28 if you have been deficient.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="competitor" style="background:#FFFBEB;border:1px solid #F59E0B;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#F59E0B;margin-bottom:8px;">Competitor: Full Micronutrient Stack</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Add all three: Vitamin D3 (3,000 IU with lunch), Magnesium Glycinate (400mg before bed), Zinc (25mg with dinner). Keep taking your greens supplement daily. Assess energy consistency at Day 30 against your Week 1 baseline.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="athlete" style="background:#F0FBFD;border:1px solid #06A5C5;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#06A5C5;margin-bottom:8px;">Athlete: Stack + Creatine Loading</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">Full micronutrient stack plus add creatine monohydrate: 5g daily with your post-training meal. Creatine phosphocreatine system directly increases high-intensity output, enabling higher training loads that demand and produce greater muscle protein synthesis response.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="elite" style="background:#F5F3FF;border:1px solid #8B5CF6;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#8B5CF6;margin-bottom:8px;">Elite: Optimize by Bloodwork</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">If your bloodwork from Week 1 is back, dose Vitamin D to target range (add 1,000 IU per 10 ng/mL gap from the 60 ng/mL target). Confirm Magnesium RBC is above 5.6 mg/dL. Zinc should be between 70 and 130 mcg/dL. Adjust doses accordingly.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-tier-block" data-tier="champion" style="background:#FEF2F2;border:1px solid #EF4444;border-radius:4px;padding:16px 20px;margin:16px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:11px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:2px;color:#EF4444;margin-bottom:8px;">Champion: Quarterly Review Protocol</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333;line-height:1.65;margin:0;">At Day 30, compare energy consistency, sleep quality, and mid-session output metrics against your pre-protocol baseline. Book a quarterly bloodwork check. Micronutrient status drifts over time as training volume changes and dietary variety shifts. Do not assume it stays optimal without verification.</p>
        </div>

        <div style="border-top:3px solid #06A5C5;background:#fff;padding:24px 28px;margin:24px 0;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:4px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 10px;">Week 4 Assignment</p>
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:15px;color:#333333;margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Add the micronutrient protocol. On Day 30, answer these three questions: How often do I crash mid-afternoon compared to Week 1? How does my training energy in the final 20 minutes compare to Week 1? How is my hunger and meal-to-meal energy consistency compared to Day 1? Those three answers tell you whether the nutrition gap is closing.</p>
        </div>

        <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin-bottom:12px;margin-top:16px;">What Success Looks Like at Day 30</h3>
        <p class="apn-nutr-body">You hit your protein target (0.9g/lb bodyweight) 5 out of 7 days per week. You are eating 4 meals daily with 25g protein minimum at each. Your carbohydrates are noticeably higher on training days than rest days. You have added a greens supplement and Vitamin D to your daily routine and taken them consistently for at least 18 of the last 30 days. Mid-afternoon energy crashes have reduced in frequency. Training energy in the last 20 minutes of sessions has improved. Those are your markers. They are measurable. Measure them.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

